  "signature": "ed25519:7c3a1f9e2b5d8a4c0f6e3b7d1a9c5f2e8b4d0a7c3f6e9b2d5a8c1f4e7b0d3a6c",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA documentation must demonstrate version-controlled solver environment, regression test suite coverage ≥80%, and traceable change management records per FDA software guidance.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA solvers (ABAQUS 2021, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1, and the FDA in-house COMSOL 6.0 environment) operate under institutional software quality management plans. Version control is enforced via Git-tagged releases; regression suites are executed prior to each study run. Achieved level 3 reflects documented SQA plans with periodic audit trails."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must include at least one benchmark problem with known analytical solution demonstrating convergence order consistent with theoretical expectations for the element formulation employed.",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and manufactured-solution benchmarks were executed for the C3D8I and SOLID186 element libraries used in the pedicle screw mesh. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical second-order expectations. No anomalous stress oscillations were detected in the threaded root regions under bending load."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change of less than 2% between the penultimate and final refinement levels, with Richardson extrapolation applied to quantify residual discretization uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the screw shank and rod-screw interface regions, which govern construct stiffness. Global element size was halved at each level (baseline 0.8 mm → 0.4 mm → 0.2 mm in critical zones). QoI change between levels 2 and 3 was 0.9% for stiffness and 1.4% for yield force. Richardson extrapolation estimated residual discretization uncertainty of ±1.1% on stiffness, incorporated into the total uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residuals must fall below 1×10⁻⁶ for all nonlinear iterations; energy balance checks must confirm equilibrium within 0.1% of applied load.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear quasi-static analyses employed full Newton-Raphson iteration with automatic load stepping. Residual norms converged to below 1×10⁻⁷ in all load steps. Energy balance diagnostics confirmed equilibrium within 0.05% across all 11 specimen simulations. No hourglassing or zero-energy mode warnings were flagged."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation execution must be governed by a written simulation execution plan (SEP) reviewed by at least one independent analyst; boundary condition application must be independently verified against the SEP prior to result extraction.",
      "rationale": "A simulation execution plan was prepared and independently reviewed by a second engineer at each participating organization. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior vertebral body, displacement-controlled superior loading fixture at 1 mm/min equivalent quasi-static rate) were verified against ASTM F1717 test setup photographs. No discrepancies were found between planned and implemented configurations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form selection must be justified by literature evidence or sensitivity analysis demonstrating that the chosen constitutive law and contact formulation reproduce the dominant load-transfer mechanisms observed experimentally.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) was modeled using a bilinear isotropic hardening law calibrated to ASTM E8 coupon data from the same material lot. Surface-to-surface penalty contact with finite sliding was applied at the screw-rod interface; friction coefficient 0.2 was selected based on published tribology literature for Ti-Ti interfaces under lubricated conditions. Sensitivity analysis showed QoI variation of <3% over friction coefficient range 0.15–0.30, confirming low sensitivity to this parameter."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material and geometric inputs must be traceable to measured values with documented uncertainty; input uncertainty must be propagated to QoI uncertainty using Monte Carlo sampling or equivalent method.",
      "rationale": "Geometry was derived from CMM measurements of three representative screws and rods from the production lot (dimensional uncertainty ±0.02 mm). Material elastic modulus and yield strength were drawn from certificate of conformance data (E = 113.8 ± 2.1 GPa, σ_y = 880 ± 15 MPa). Latin hypercube sampling with N=200 runs was used to propagate input uncertainty; resulting QoI uncertainty was ±4.1% on stiffness and ±5.3% on yield force."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test sample population must be drawn from production-representative hardware with documented lot traceability; sample size must be sufficient to characterize inter-specimen variability at the 90% confidence level.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from a single production lot of 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screws and 5.5 mm titanium rods. Lot certificates of conformance confirmed dimensional and material compliance. Sample size analysis using a t-distribution approach indicated N=11 provides 90% confidence interval on mean stiffness of ±6.2%, deemed adequate for the medium-risk COU. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation was 3.8%, within expected bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of loading scenarios represented in the COU, including at minimum two distinct load magnitudes or configurations; single-condition testing requires documented justification and risk acceptance.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single loading configuration (ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending at 5° offset) at ambient temperature. The COU is restricted to this specific test configuration, and clinical loading diversity is not within scope of this validation activity. The single-condition limitation is acknowledged as a gap; however, the COU boundary explicitly excludes fatigue and multi-axial loading scenarios. This factor is assessed as achieved level 2 against required level 3, representing the one identified shortfall in the overall credibility assessment. The team accepted this gap based on the medium model influence rating and the availability of independent bench test confirmation for the primary QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between simulation inputs and physical test parameters was established through a formal input mapping table. Screw geometry in the FEA was derived from CMM measurements of the identical hardware used in testing. Applied displacement boundary conditions were mapped directly to the actuator displacement records from each test. Torque preload on the set screws was measured with a calibrated torque wrench (±0.05 N·m) and replicated in the model via bolt pretension elements. The mapping table was reviewed and signed off by both the simulation lead and the experimental lead prior to result comparison. No unresolved equivalency discrepancies were identified. The structured mapping process followed the ASME V&V 40 Table 3 recommended practice for input equivalency documentation, and the level-3 achievement reflects full quantitative traceability of all primary inputs without reliance on assumed or surrogate values. This factor is considered the strongest in the assessment from an input-fidelity standpoint, and the detailed mapping record is archived in the study technical file under document reference NTF-2024-0047-EQ."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Output comparison must use a quantitative metric (e.g., E/uval) with a pre-specified threshold; the threshold must be documented prior to unblinding of simulation results relative to experimental data.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was pre-specified at a threshold of 1.96 (95% confidence band) in the validation plan registered prior to test execution. Achieved values were 1.31 (stiffness), 1.54 (yield force), and 1.89 (force at 40 mm), all below the threshold. The 10% absolute difference criterion was also pre-specified and met for all three QoIs across all 11 specimens."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must be directly linked to the device's intended use and the regulatory submission claims; each QoI must have a documented clinical or mechanical significance rationale.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly correspond to the mechanical performance claims in the 510(k) submission. Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spinal segment; yield force indicates structural integrity under physiological loading; force at 40 mm is the standard measure of ultimate load-bearing capacity. All three are clinically meaningful and directly supported by the regulatory pathway."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted under conditions sufficiently representative of the COU to support extrapolation of conclusions; any gaps between validation conditions and COU conditions must be explicitly characterized.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the regulatory test method (ASTM F1717) under which the device will be characterized in the 510(k) submission. The FEA model geometry, material, and boundary conditions are drawn from the same production hardware and test protocol. The only noted gap is the single-condition test coverage addressed under the Test Conditions factor. Overall, the validation activity is judged highly relevant to the COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required level. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) is accepted on the basis of the medium model influence rating, the explicit COU boundary restriction to the ASTM F1717 single-condition protocol, and the availability of independent experimental confirmation across two laboratories. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support a medium-assurance claim for the non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending FEA model.",
